          "body": "The chapter's punchline arrives in 1:14, almost as an aside but doing massive structural work. After the catena has proven the Son's supremacy, the author asks rhetorically: *are not the angels all ministering spirits, sent out to render service for the sake of those who will inherit salvation?* In one sentence the angels are demoted to their proper place — not objects of worship, not mediators of the new covenant, not rivals to the Son, but *servants of the saints*. The drifting readers, tempted to elevate angelic mediation (the law was given through angels, Galatians 3:19; Acts 7:53), are being told that angels work *for them*, not above them. The believer who has the Son seated at God's right hand does not need an angelic intercessor — and the angels themselves know it. This sets up chapter 2's *therefore*: if angels serve us because we are heirs of salvation, *we must pay much closer attention to what we have heard, lest we drift away* (2:1)."
